// 09_stack_and_workbench.bund
// The workbench, stack manipulation, and named stacks.

// ── WORKBENCH ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// The `.` command moves the top of the current stack to the workbench.
// Commands with `.` suffix read one argument from the workbench instead.

42 .                // move 42 to workbench; stack is now empty
"value from workbench: " print
println.            // print the workbench value (42) with newline

// Workbench + arithmetic: one operand from stack, one from workbench
100 .               // workbench = 100
58 +.               // 58 + workbench(100) = 158
println             // 158

// Workbench as a temporary holding register while building up a computation
"intermediate result" .     // stash a label
10 7 *                      // 70 on stack
convert.to_string           // "70"
concat_with_space           // join stashed label + "70"
println                     // "intermediate result 70"

// ── DUP AND SWAP ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// dup: copy the top value
7 dup * println             // 7*7 = 49

// swap: exchange top two values
1 2 swap                    // stack: [ 1 | 2 ] → [ 2 | 1 ]
- println                   // 2 - 1 = 1  (TOS is 2, next is 1)

// ── NAMED STACKS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// @name switches the active stack to the named stack.
// Values pushed afterward go onto that stack.

@scratch             // switch to "scratch" stack
"value on scratch stack" println

@main                // switch back to main stack
"back on main stack" println

// Named stacks allow parallel workspaces.
@accumulator
0                    // push initial accumulator value

1 + . +.             // add workbench value — simplified pattern
// (detailed accumulator patterns use while/for)

@main
"done with accumulator stack" println

// ── EXECUTE FROM STACK ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

// execute: run a value that happens to be a command name or lambda
"println" execute           // ERROR illustration — push a string that IS a command name
                            // and execute resolves it as a command

// More typical: store a lambda reference and execute later
`square                     // push pointer to "square" (must be registered earlier)
                            // execute.  ← would call it

// ── COMBINING STACK TECHNIQUES ────────────────────────────────────────────────

// Compute (a² + b²) for a=3, b=4 using dup and arithmetic
3 dup * .       // a² = 9, saved to workbench
4 dup *         // b² = 16, on stack
+.              // 16 + workbench(9) = 25
println         // 25
